law.text:
The board may refuse to license or renew, or may suspend, probate or revoke the license of any podiatrist or in addition to such punishment or in lieu thereof may impose a fine not to exceed five hundred dollars ($500) for each offense, upon proof that he:
Has been convicted of a felony;
Has been convicted of a misdemeanor involving moral turpitude or conduct likely to deceive or defraud the public;
Has employed, hired, procured or induced a person not licensed to practice podiatry in this state so to practice;
Has aided or abetted in the practice of podiatry a person not licensed to practice podiatry in this state;
Has been granted a license upon a mistake of a material fact;
Has violated any provision of KRS 311.390 to 311.510;
Has become drug addicted;
Has become a chronic or persistent alcoholic;
Has developed such physical or mental disability, or other condition whereby continued practice is dangerous to patients or to the public;
Has violated any order of suspension, or the terms or the conditions of any order of probation, issued by the board;
Has engaged in, or attempted to engage in the practice of podiatry under a false or assumed name;
Has willfully violated a confidential communication;
Has acted in a grossly negligent or willful manner which is inconsistent with the practice of podiatry;
Is unfit or incompetent to practice podiatry by reason of gross negligence or other causes including but not limited to being unable to practice podiatry with reasonable skill or safety;
Has a license to practice as a podiatrist denied, limited, suspended, probated or revoked in another jurisdiction on grounds sufficient to cause a license to be denied, limited, suspended, probated or revoked in this Commonwealth; or
Has engaged in conduct likely to deceive or defraud the public.
